<!-- Body -->
<article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12 py-16">
    <p class="text-on-surface-variant text-lg leading-relaxed font-body mb-8 first-letter:text-5xl first-letter:font-headline first-letter:text-primary first-letter:float-left first-letter:mr-3 first-letter:mt-1">
        The Fireside Editorial was born from a simple belief: the traditions we keep in winter say something true about who we are. Not the grand, commercial version of the holidays — the quiet one. The one that smells like ginger and pine and lives in the muscle memory of your hands when you fold the same ornament paper your grandmother taught you.
    </p>

    <div class="prose-fireside font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <h2>Why We Exist</h2>
        <p>We started this journal because we noticed something: the best parts of winter aren't sold in stores. They're passed down at kitchen tables, whispered during late-night cocoa, and stitched into stockings that take longer to make than any reasonable person would admit.</p>
        <p>Every article we publish is an attempt to hold onto that. To document the rituals — large and small — that make the darkest months feel the most luminous. We write about baking and knitting and caroling not because they're quaint, but because they're real. They connect us backward to the people who did this before us and forward to the ones who'll do it after.</p>

        <h2>What We Believe</h2>
        <p>We believe a gingerbread house with a crooked chimney is more beautiful than a perfect one. We believe midnight cocoa is a form of meditation. We believe the best gift you can give someone is a tradition they'll carry with them for the rest of their life.</p>
        <p>We also believe that the internet has enough noise and not enough warmth. The Fireside Editorial is our small corner of quiet — a place where the pace slows down, the prose takes its time, and every image is meant to feel like a memory you haven't made yet.</p>

        <h2>How It Works</h2>
        <p>Each journal entry is a curated exploration of a single tradition. We pair original editorial writing with hand-selected products we genuinely believe in — the kind of things we'd recommend to a friend, not a customer. When you see a "Curated Pick" at the bottom of an article, that's a product our editors chose because it belongs in the story we're telling.</p>
        <p>We also invite you to share your own traditions. The best stories aren't ours — they're yours. The ones about the candle your family lights every solstice, or the recipe your great-aunt refused to write down until she finally did, on the back of an envelope, in handwriting only she could read.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <div class="mt-16 p-10 bg-surface-container rounded-xl border border-outline-variant/30 text-center">
